parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Fuel Leak and Gasoline Smell in Cold Weather
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The fuel leak and strong gasoline smell in cold weather can cause headaches, nausea, and pose a serious fire hazard, potentially leading to accidents or injuries.
symptoms: Strong smell of gasoline or fuel in the cabin
especially when the heater is turned on
fuel leaks or drips from the fuel lines
fuel smell outside the vehicle
burning sensation in the nose and throat.

parsedComplaintsResult.issueCategory: Fuel Line Leaks and Gas Odor in Cold Weather
parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Fuel leaks can cause a fire hazard, and gas odors can lead to health problems, including headaches, nausea, and dizziness.
symptoms: Strong gas smell inside the cabin
fuel leaks under the manifold
fuel smell when idling or driving in cold weather
gas fumes entering the cabin through the climate control system.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the lower control arm can cause loss of control, accidents, or leave the driver stranded.
symptoms: The vehicle may vibrate or shake
the steering wheel may jerk or pull to one side
the wheel may turn inward or outward
and the vehicle may make loud noises.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The inadequate repair of the lower control arm under the recall may lead to further failures, accidents, or injuries.
symptoms: The vehicle may exhibit similar symptoms as before the recall repair
including vibration
shaking
or loud noises.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The corrosion of the lower control arm can cause it to fail, leading to loss of control, accidents, or injuries.
symptoms: The vehicle may vibrate or shake
the steering wheel may jerk or pull to one side
and the vehicle may make loud noises.
